Approach:
Scan the array once while maintaining a sorted set of values whose indices are at least x behind the current index. For each i ≥ x, all valid partners j must satisfy j ≤ i − x. Keep all nums[j] for j ≤ i − x in a balanced BST; the closest candidates to nums[i] are its predecessor and successor in the set. Update the answer with these two.

- Time: O(n log n)
- Space: O(n)

Java (using TreeSet):
public class Solution {
    public int minAbsoluteDifference(int[] nums, int x) {
        if (x == 0) return 0; // i == j allowed, diff 0
        int n = nums.length;
        java.util.TreeSet<Integer> set = new java.util.TreeSet<>();
        int ans = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for (int i = x; i < n; i++) {
            set.add(nums[i - x]);

            Integer lo = set.floor(nums[i]);
            if (lo != null) ans = Math.min(ans, nums[i] - lo);

            Integer hi = set.ceiling(nums[i]);
            if (hi != null) ans = Math.min(ans, hi - nums[i]);

            if (ans == 0) return 0;
        }
        return ans;
    }
}

Python (requires sortedcontainers.SortedList; if unavailable, use a balanced BST implementation):
from sortedcontainers import SortedList

def minAbsoluteDifference(nums, x):
    if x == 0:
        return 0
    sl = SortedList()
    ans = float('inf')
    for i in range(x, len(nums)):
        sl.add(nums[i - x])
        v = nums[i]
        pos = sl.bisect_left(v)
        if pos < len(sl):
            ans = min(ans, abs(sl[pos] - v))
        if pos > 0:
            ans = min(ans, abs(v - sl[pos - 1]))
        if ans == 0:
            return 0
    return ans

This checks every pair with index distance at least x exactly once (when processing the larger index), and querying predecessor/successor yields the minimal absolute difference.

The split is possible if and only if no value appears more than twice. Each half can contain at most one copy of any value, so with two halves, a value can appear at most twice overall. If all frequencies are ≤ 2, place one of each pair in different halves and distribute singletons to balance sizes.

